@Donnie_Eagle Sure. But this doesn't make the Yen a safe haven. It's a funding currency behaving like a safe haven. Initial wave of risk liquidation goes to Yen, but then the correlation should break down on rotation from Yen to real safe haven assets. So eventually USDJPY up even in risk off.

@CyFerpunk @VinnyLingham US equities had nearly a decade of immunity to bad news on account of central bank policy that incentivized excessive risk taking, in an effort to artificially prop global sentiment. It's fair to assume the reversal of this policy is triggering the opposite reaction.

FX traders have been having a hard time calling for US Dollar upside despite flight to safety, given US protectionism. But if the Yen, which isn't even a safe haven, can rally in risk off, I think it's fair to assume the Dollar, which is a safe haven, should be able to find bids.

One of the best ways to identify an early stage of a bear market is to watch how the market behaves into rallies. The way a trend will go from well supported on dips, to all of a sudden, well capped into rallies, is one of those things that really drives home the change going on.
This latest $GBPUSD pullback will be more legitimate in terms of signalling a meaningful top if $EURUSD breaks back below 1.2350.

$GBPUSD: I've been skeptical about the Pound's ability to extend much more than what we've already seen at this point in 2018 and have been looking for the market to go through a more significant correction before bullish continuation. Still think 1.3600 area pullback realistic.

US protectionism has been a US Dollar killer over the past several months, though I believe we'll soon see an intensification of selling in the equities market that will invite renewed USD interest on traditional safe haven flow. Look for Euro upside to be limited to 1.2700 area.

If you‚Äôre wondering if soft USD policy will prevent the Buck from rallying in fight to safety, just look at the Yen. The Japanese currency is nothing more than a funding currency and yet it still rallies in risk off. So YES..the Dollar can rally in risk off despite US policy IMO.

Important to recognize shift going on. What might be dovish today is completely different than past. Dovish used to be the #Fed delivering less than expected, but now, dovish is the Fed not delivering more than expected.    So let down not about 2 instead of 3 but 3 instead of 4.

Not too sure there was so much in the Fed message to justify aggressive selling of the US Dollar. It's true, growth language was downgraded to 'moderate' and dot plot still showed 3 hikes...BUT actual growth forecasts raised and more hikes projected beyond 2018.   Dovish? ü§î
